<div id="review_3830371617" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3830371617" />
    <a title="Ebony Eldritch" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/121834919-ebony-eldritch"><img alt="Ebony Eldritch" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1619117492p2/121834919.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3830371617?book_show_action=true">Feb 15, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ebony Eldritch" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ebony Eldritch" href="/user/show/121834919-ebony-eldritch">Ebony Eldritch</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/121834919-ebony-eldritch?shelf=gothic-horror">gothic-horror</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3830371617" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5585976639827655583">Another of Poe&apos;s classic works of gothic horror which shows us a cruel man with cruel intentions as he forms and subsequently enacts a plot against his former close friend, the ironically names Fortunato who, by the end of the story, is anything but fortunate.<br/><br/>After luring his former friend into a cruel trap concluding in an inevitably slow and painful death, with the promise of the titular cask of amontillado, Montresor continues with his life for the next fifty years, his terrible deeds seeming</span>
  <span id="freeText5585976639827655583" style="display:none">Another of Poe's classic works of gothic horror which shows us a cruel man with cruel intentions as he forms and subsequently enacts a plot against his former close friend, the ironically names Fortunato who, by the end of the story, is anything but fortunate.<br /><br />After luring his former friend into a cruel trap concluding in an inevitably slow and painful death, with the promise of the titular cask of amontillado, Montresor continues with his life for the next fifty years, his terrible deeds seemingly having failed to weigh upon him in any meaningful way.<br /><br />Whilst the writing of this tale is, as always with Poe, wonderful, I personally found the lack of backstory regarding the split in Montresor and Fortunato's friendship to be a tantalising thread which, to my utter dissatisfaction, was never pulled. This remains to be my only criticism of the work; that it would have been more interesting to see Montresor actively justify his actions by citing the initial incident, instead only mentioning that Fortunato had failed to apologise for whatever this transgression may have been.<br /><br />Aside from this admittedly minute detail, I have no complaints at all about this otherwise creepy and unsettling work. I do hope none of my friends offer me a drink from a cask of amontillado, else I may have to stop speaking to them!</span>
  <a data-text-id="5585976639827655583" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


